## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely in .NET Core+
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws** — no longer meaningful
3. The old pattern of forcibly killing threads has no direct equivalent — cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken` is the modern replacement

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, just like the original thread.Join(timeout) did
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception aggregates to match original behavior
            throw ex.InnerExceptions[0];
        }
    }

    // Convenience overload for fire-and-forget style (no cancellation support)
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
        {
            ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
            return work();
        }, timeout);
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No forced termination** | Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, cancellation is *cooperative*. The `work` delegate **must** check `ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` or pass the token to APIs it calls (HTTP, DB, I/O). Without this, the work keeps running after timeout. |
| **Orphaned work** | If `work` ignores the token, the `Task` runs to completion in the background even after you've thrown `TimeoutException`. This is a fundamental behavioral change. |
| **`default(T)` race condition** | The original code had a subtle bug — `result` could be read as `default` if the thread was aborted mid-assignment. The task-based version eliminates this. |
| **Exception wrapping** | `Task.Run` wraps exceptions in `AggregateException`. The overload above unwraps single exceptions to preserve original semantics. |
| **Sync-over-async** | `GetAwaiter().GetResult()` blocks the calling thread, matching the original synchronous API. If you can change callers, prefer an `async` version instead. |

### Preferred Async Version (if callers can be updated)

```csharp
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
    Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

    try
    {
        return await work(cts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

### Usage Comparison

```csharp
// OLD (.NET Framework)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => SlowQuery(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// NEW (.NET 8) — pass the token through to cancellable APIs
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => SlowQuery(ct), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

The fundamental shift: **.NET Framework let you kill work forcibly; .NET 8 requires the work to opt in to cancellation.** Any long-running code that previously relied on `Thread.Abort` as a safety net must now be audited to ensure it respects `CancellationToken`.
